{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7f97be20-de8a-4617-8edf-5fc72c749a36","content":"\n\nIn your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Scenario | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| App goes to background | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| App returns to foreground | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n\n> `Backgrounding` is **iOS/Mac Catalyst only** — it fires when the app is about to be suspended and lets you save state.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6293ffe0-9962-4ddf-90d5-8acbe620f24e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":409},"id":"6edefdb7-edd9-4615-9ee7-a1a92f99b522","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:48:54.116Z","parentId":"a3376f6e-6017-47a0-a5bd-c17cd2e6a120"}
